<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
The new genus superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Carterocephalus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carterocephalus" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Carterocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lederer, 1852, although it is distinguishable from the latter with regards to the following characters: hindwing undersides with silver spots, a deeply bifurcated V-shaped uncus, juxta a heart-shaped ring, and valvae asymmetrical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
The new genus contains only the type species 
<taxonomicName authority="Hou, Fan &amp; Chiba, 2021" authorityName="Hou, Fan &amp; Chiba" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pulchroptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchroptera pulchra" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Pulchroptera pulchra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Leech, 1891) comb. nov., with the nominotypical subspecies and a further subspecies, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hou, Fan &amp; Chiba, 2021" authorityName="Hou, Fan &amp; Chiba" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pulchroptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchroptera pulchra subsp. ops" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pulchra" subSpecies="ops">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Pulchroptera pulchra ops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Grum-Grshimaïlo">Grum-Grshimailo</normalizedToken>
, 1891) comb. nov. According to the description of 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, WH" journalOrPublisher="British Museum (Natural History), London" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" publicationUrl="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48223970" refId="B6" refString="Evans, WH, 1949. A Catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia &amp; Australia in the British Museum (Natural History). British Museum (Natural History). London, 502 pp. https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48223970" title="A Catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia &amp; Australia in the British Museum (Natural History). British Museum (Natural History). London, 502 pp." url="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48223970" year="1949">Evans (1949)</bibRefCitation>
, in 
<taxonomicName authority="pulchra" authorityName="Hou, Fan &amp; Chiba" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pulchroptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchroptera pulchra subsp. pulchra" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pulchra" subSpecies="pulchra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Pulchroptera pulchra pulchra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. the upper side of the hindwing has a cell spot and the submarginal markings are notably more conspicuous, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hou, Fan &amp; Chiba, 2021" authorityName="Hou, Fan &amp; Chiba" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pulchroptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchroptera pulchra subsp. ops" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pulchra" subSpecies="ops">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Pulchroptera pulchra ops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. the upper side of the hindwing lacks a cell spot and has conspicuous submarginal markings. Whether the subspecies status of the latter is valid is subject to further verification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
The name of the genus is taken from the specific epithet of the type species 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘pulchr-’">'pulchr-'</normalizedToken>
, meaning beautiful, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘optera’">'optera'</normalizedToken>
, meaning wing. The gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
